# Server
PORT=3001
NODE_ENV=development
# Comma-separated list of literal allowed origins.
CORS_ORIGIN=http://localhost:3000
# Optional regex (as a string) for dynamic origins like Vercel preview
# URLs. A request is allowed if its Origin matches any literal in
# CORS_ORIGIN OR this pattern. Leave unset in dev.
# Example for this project's preview deploys:
# CORS_ORIGIN_PATTERN=^https://itinly-[a-z0-9-]+-justmarks-projects\.vercel\.app$

# Google OAuth — primary client (create at
# https://console.cloud.google.com/apis/credentials). Powers sign-in, Drive
# storage, and Calendar sync. Configure with scopes: openid, email, profile,
# drive.file, calendar. NOT gmail.readonly — Gmail uses a separate client
# below to keep the primary client off the CASA-required restricted-scope
# path.
#
# The redirect URI used by the web flow is built at runtime from the
# browser origin (`<origin>/auth/callback`) — register it in the Google
# Cloud Console for each origin you serve from (dev: http://localhost:3000,
# prod: your Vercel origin). No GOOGLE_REDIRECT_URI env var needed.
GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID=your-client-id.apps.googleusercontent.com
GOOGLE_CLIENT_SECRET=your-client-secret

# Google OAuth — Gmail client. A second OAuth client used only for the
# restricted `gmail.readonly` scope powering the email-scan feature. Split
# from the primary client so the primary can clear standard verification
# without the whole app needing a CASA assessment. Configure with scopes:
# openid, email, profile, gmail.readonly. Same redirect URIs as the primary
# client (the callback page reads `state.flow` to know which exchange to
# run). Either var unset disables Gmail scanning entirely.
GOOGLE_GMAIL_CLIENT_ID=your-gmail-client-id.apps.googleusercontent.com
GOOGLE_GMAIL_CLIENT_SECRET=your-gmail-client-secret

# Microsoft (Azure AD) OAuth client. Used by Supabase Microsoft sign-in
# AND by the server for Microsoft Graph mail (Mail.Read) + calendar
# (Calendars.ReadWrite). Unlike Google, Microsoft mail + calendar scopes
# aren't gated behind a CASA-style external assessment, so one Azure app
# registration serves every capability. TENANT_ID = `common` for
# multi-tenant (any work/school/personal MS account), `consumers` for
# personal only, `organizations` for work/school only, or a tenant GUID
# for single-tenant. Leave the secret unset to disable Microsoft mail +
# calendar integration (Supabase sign-in still works — Supabase has its
# own copy of these credentials in its provider dashboard).
MICROSOFT_CLIENT_ID=your-azure-app-client-id
MICROSOFT_CLIENT_SECRET=your-azure-app-client-secret
MICROSOFT_TENANT_ID=common

# Anthropic API (for email parsing)
ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=sk-ant-your-key-here

# Sentry (server). DSN for the Express server's Sentry project. Unset in
# dev / CI to disable error reporting entirely (the server logs a line at
# boot and `reportError` becomes a no-op). Get this from Sentry → Settings
# → Projects → <project> → Client Keys (DSN). Use a SEPARATE project from
# the browser DSN below so server and client errors don't fight for issue
# grouping.
SENTRY_DSN=

# Upstash Redis (optional but recommended for production).
# When both are set, the server persists refresh tokens and share-link
# entries so they survive process restarts. Get these from
# Upstash Console → Databases → REST API. They are per-database
# credentials; do NOT use the account / management API key.
UPSTASH_REDIS_REST_URL=https://your-db.upstash.io
UPSTASH_REDIS_REST_TOKEN=your-rest-token

# At-rest encryption for refresh tokens stored in Redis. When set, the
# `refreshToken` field of each persisted entry is AES-256-GCM-encrypted
# so a Redis dump alone isn't enough to grant access to user accounts.
# Generate with: openssl rand -hex 32  (must be exactly 64 hex chars).
# Leave unset to fall through to plaintext storage (fine for dev/tests,
# not recommended for production). Rotating the key invalidates all
# existing entries — affected users will have to sign in again.
TOKEN_ENCRYPTION_KEY=

# Web Push (RFC 8292 / VAPID). Required to deliver share-invite and
# trip-activity push notifications. Generate once with:
#   npx web-push generate-vapid-keys
# Persist both halves; the public half also goes into the frontend
# (NEXT_PUBLIC_VAPID_PUBLIC_KEY) so the browser can subscribe. The
# subject is a `mailto:` URL push providers use to reach the app owner
# if a push fails. Either VAPID_*_KEY unset disables push delivery — the
# server logs a warning and `/api/v1/push/*` becomes a no-op so dev /
# tests run without keys configured.
VAPID_PUBLIC_KEY=
VAPID_PRIVATE_KEY=
VAPID_SUBJECT=mailto:hello@itinly.app

# Supabase Auth (Phase 3). Setting this flips `requireAuth` into
# coexistence mode — it accepts Supabase JWTs in addition to legacy
# Google access tokens. JWKS is derived from the URL; we never need
# the anon / service-role keys server-side. See
# docs/supabase-auth-setup.md for the Azure + provider setup.
SUPABASE_URL=https://your-project-ref.supabase.co

# Postgres connection string (Phase 1+). Required when storage involves
# Postgres OR when SUPABASE_URL is set (Supabase-authed users live in
# Postgres exclusively). From Railway, use the Supabase Session pooler
# URL — Direct connections are IPv6-only and Railway's outbound network
# is IPv4-only. Format:
#   postgresql://postgres.<project-ref>:<password>@aws-X-<region>.pooler.supabase.com:5432/postgres
# Drop `?sslmode=verify-full` — the pooler's TLS chain doesn't validate
# against system root CAs; use `?sslmode=require` or omit the param
# entirely. See docs/supabase-auth-setup.md §6 for the full rationale.
DATABASE_URL=

# Storage backend (Phase 1 of the Drive→Supabase migration). Picks
# which StorageProvider per-user requests resolve to:
#   drive    — every user reads/writes their own Drive folder
#              (production default)
#   postgres — every user lives in Postgres (future state)
#   memory   — dev/test only (no real auth)
#   unset    — defaults to `drive` in NODE_ENV=production, `memory` in
#              dev
STORAGE_BACKEND=

# Comma-separated list of Google `sub` user IDs to route to Postgres
# instead of Drive when STORAGE_BACKEND=drive. Phase 1 dogfooding flag
# for moving specific users off Drive before the global cutover.
STORAGE_POSTGRES_USERS=

# Verbose logging from the email-scan pipeline (Gmail fetch, parse,
# dedup, apply). Off by default to keep Railway logs quiet. Set to `1`
# while debugging email-scan issues.
DEBUG_EMAIL_SCAN=

# Frontend (apps/web)
NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL=http://localhost:3001/api/v1
NEXT_PUBLIC_GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID=your-client-id.apps.googleusercontent.com
# Public half of the Gmail OAuth client (matches GOOGLE_GMAIL_CLIENT_ID on
# the server). Embedded in the bundle so the browser can build the consent
# URL when a user opts into email scanning. Unset disables the in-app
# "Connect Gmail" CTA.
NEXT_PUBLIC_GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID_GMAIL=your-gmail-client-id.apps.googleusercontent.com
NEXT_PUBLIC_GOOGLE_MAPS_API_KEY=your-maps-api-key.apps.googleusercontent.com

# Public half of the VAPID key pair (must match VAPID_PUBLIC_KEY on the
# server). Embedded in the browser bundle so the service worker can
# subscribe. Unset disables the in-app "Enable notifications" affordance.
NEXT_PUBLIC_VAPID_PUBLIC_KEY=

# Sentry (browser). Must use the `NEXT_PUBLIC_` prefix so Next.js inlines
# the value into the static bundle at build time — the browser SDK reads
# it via `process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_SENTRY_DSN`. Unset disables browser
# error reporting (init becomes a no-op, `reportError` is silent). Use a
# SEPARATE project from `SENTRY_DSN` above; a `NEXT_PUBLIC_` value is
# visible in shipped JS, so don't reuse the server DSN here.
NEXT_PUBLIC_SENTRY_DSN=

# Supabase Auth (Phase 3b frontend cutover). When both are set, the
# login pages route Google + Microsoft sign-in through Supabase Auth
# instead of the legacy custom Google OAuth flow. The anon key is
# safe to ship in the public bundle — row-level-security policies on
# the Postgres side are what gate data access. Get both from the
# Supabase dashboard → Project Settings → API.
NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL=https://your-project-ref.supabase.co
NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY=your-anon-public-key

# OAuth preview-relay configuration. Google's OAuth client only allows
# fixed redirect URIs (no wildcards), but Vercel previews get a unique
# hostname per deploy. To make sign-in work on previews, the web app
# relays the OAuth round-trip through production.
#
# - NEXT_PUBLIC_PROD_ORIGIN: production origin (the only redirect URI
#   registered with Google). Set on BOTH Production and Preview in
#   Vercel — previews use it to know where to relay through; prod
#   compares against it to detect "I'm not the intended target, relay".
#   Leave unset locally — localhost auto-skips the relay.
# - NEXT_PUBLIC_PREVIEW_ORIGIN_PATTERN: anchored regex matching allowed
#   preview origins (full URL incl. scheme). The relay refuses to
#   bounce OAuth codes to anything that doesn't match. Set on
#   Production only — that's where the relay runs. Mirrors the server's
#   CORS_ORIGIN_PATTERN. If you've assigned a stable preview alias
#   (e.g. preview.itinly.app via a Vercel branch-domain pointing at the
#   `preview` branch — see docs/vercel-setup.md), include it in the
#   alternation so the OAuth relay can bounce through that origin too.
NEXT_PUBLIC_PROD_ORIGIN=https://your-app.vercel.app
NEXT_PUBLIC_PREVIEW_ORIGIN_PATTERN=^(https://itinly-[a-z0-9-]+-justmarks-projects\.vercel\.app|https://preview\.itinly\.app)$